Sep 22 index value = 296.808, <1 higher than Aug, after July and Aug saw gentle declines.Seasonality, along with Fed actions, is likely dampening price growth.(296.808 / 278.802 - 1) * 100% = 6.46% inflation over the 9 months from Dec 21 to Sep 22.(296.808 / 296.171 - 1) * 100% = 0.22% mom inflation.3 months to go in the forecast period.At 0.3% mom inflation for the next 3 months, the end result would be (296.808*1.003^3 / 278.802 - 1) * 100% = 7.42%. I think this is a likely upper limit at this point. Even if mom inflation were 0.5% each remaining month, inflation would be 8.06%, and I think the equivalent of 0.5% mom inflation for the remainder of the forecast period is unlikely at this point.Given that July and Aug saw slight decreases, I don't think further decreases are out of the question, either. So I'm raising my forecast on bin 3.I suspect that we'll see the equivalent of roughly -0.1% to +0.2% for the remainder of the forecast period, but I could be very wrong. The value of the index for Dec 21 was 278.802. March 22 value = 287.504. 287.504/278.802 = 1.031. So, there has been 3.1% inflation so far from Dec 21 to Mar 22. Extrapolating at this rate, annual inflation in Dec 22 would be 1.031^(12/3) = 1.130 => 13.0%. The Fed has signaled that it will intervene some to reduce inflation, but there are limits. Pandemic dislocations, the war in Ukraine, and at this point, inflation expectations are fueling further inflation. The range of possibilities is broad. I expect the war in Ukraine to have largely wound down by December, and that could help some prices. But I expect pandemic price increases to continue, albeit hopefully more slowly. Hopefully, the chip situation will be partly resolved, and hopefully, shipping will have improved. Food prices could still be quite high. Hopefully, energy prices won't be as bad through the remainder of the year, as demand falls in warmer months. But I don't want to rule out any but the lowest bin at this time. https://fred.stlouisfed.org/series/CPIAUCNS
